3
00:01:16,316 --> 00:01:18,886
<i>人类如何了解未知
<i>How does one come to know The Unknowable?

4
00:01:19,086 --> 00:01:21,696
<i>人类需要什么技能
<i>What faculties must a man possess?

5
00:01:21,896 --> 00:01:23,856
<i>自从人类发现鲸油
<i>Since it was discovered that whale oil

6
00:01:24,006 --> 00:01:27,156
<i>可以以前所未有的方式点亮我们的城市
<i>could light our cities in ways never achieved before,

7
00:01:27,356 --> 00:01:29,486
<i>全世界需求量暴涨
<i>it created global demand.

8
00:01:29,686 --> 00:01:33,306
<i>使人类开始向
<i>It had pushed man to venture further and further

9
00:01:33,506 --> 00:01:36,076
<i>海洋更深处冒险
<i>into The Deep, Blue Unknown.

10
00:01:36,276 --> 00:01:38,586
<i>我们不知道海洋的深度
<i>We know not its depths,

11
00:01:38,786 --> 00:01:41,486
<i>也不了解海洋里的生物
<i>nor the host of creatures that live there.

12
00:01:41,686 --> 00:01:45,136
<i>怪物是否真的存在
<i>Monsters, are they real?

13
00:01:56,006 --> 00:02:00,076
<i>或者这些故事只是让我们对海洋隐藏的秘密有所敬畏
<i>Or do the stories exist only to make us respect the sea's dark secret?

14
00:02:08,006 --> 00:02:11,076
楠塔基特岛 马萨诸塞州 1850年二月

15
00:02:13,646 --> 00:02:15,806
<i>这个问题使我即苦恼又兴奋
<i>The question both vexes and excites me,

16
00:02:16,006 --> 00:02:19,716
<i>也是我再次向您写信请求一次会面的原因
<i>and is the reason I've written you a second time to request a meeting.

17
00:02:19,816 --> 00:02:21,086
<i>一次和您交谈的机会 先生
<i>A conversation with you, Sir,

18
00:02:21,146 --> 00:02:24,506
<i>我相信这会对我将要写的小说有很大帮助
<i>I believe will serve me well for the novel I intend to write,

19
00:02:24,706 --> 00:02:27,626
<i>小说暂且名为 白鲸记
<i>currently entitled Moby Dick

20
00:02:28,126 --> 00:02:30,716
<i>我期望您能考虑我的提议
<i>I hope you will reconsider my offer.

21
00:02:32,316 --> 00:02:37,776
<i>未知 我的想象力始终想冒险的地方
<i>The Unknown, that is where my imagination yearns to venture.

22
00:02:39,006 --> 00:02:41,196
<i>始终折磨我的问题是
<i>And so, the question plagues me still:

23
00:02:42,216 --> 00:02:44,916
<i>人类如何才能探索未知
<i>How does a man come to know The Unknowable?

24
00:02:45,756 --> 00:02:48,846
<i>此致 赫尔曼·梅尔维尔
<i>Sincerely, Herman Melville.

25
00:02:49,666 --> 00:02:51,466
我们打烊了
We're closed!

26
00:02:51,946 --> 00:02:53,976
8点后不接客
No borders after eight o'clock.

27
00:03:04,406 --> 00:03:06,006
你居然来了
You came.

28
00:03:15,056 --> 00:03:17,466
亲爱的 有人来看你
There's someone here for you, My Love.

29
00:03:17,666 --> 00:03:18,666
汤姆·尼克森
Tom Nickerson?

30
00:03:22,066 --> 00:03:23,466
赫尔曼·梅尔维尔
Herman Melville.

31
00:03:23,866 --> 00:03:25,836
我们收到了你的来信
We received your letter.

32
00:03:26,816 --> 00:03:30,926
你要么走投无路要么是个傻子大老远跑来楠塔基特
You're either a desperate man or a fool to come all the way to Nantucket.

33
00:03:33,056 --> 00:03:36,326
我的提议还在
Well, my offer still stands.

34
00:03:36,526 --> 00:03:39,096
3个月的住宿换一晚的交谈
Three months'lodgings for a single night's talk.

35
00:03:40,656 --> 00:03:42,486
<i>这是我所有的钱了
<i>It's all I have in the world.

36
00:03:42,836 --> 00:03:45,186
<i>但我更愿意看作是一次投资
<i>But I'd prefer to think of it as an investment.

37
00:03:46,356 --> 00:03:48,706
我想要你告诉我
I want you to tell me what happened...

38
00:03:48,906 --> 00:03:50,506
埃塞克斯号发生了什么
to the Essex.

39
00:03:56,986 --> 00:03:59,286
你觉得发生了什么
Well,what do you think happened?

40
00:03:59,486 --> 00:04:02,296
有传言埃塞克斯号
There are rumblings,rumors that the Essex...

41
00:04:02,446 --> 00:04:05,846
你想要什么 期望听到什么故事
What do you want?What story do you expect to hear?

42
00:04:06,046 --> 00:04:08,026
白鲸的故事
That of The Whale.

43
00:04:11,286 --> 00:04:14,176
埃塞克斯号搁浅了 有完整的报告
The Essex ran aground, there was a full inquiry.

44
00:04:14,276 --> 00:04:16,796
我觉得那份报告不是事实全部
I believe the inquiry was less than truthful.

45
00:04:18,506 --> 00:04:18,996
滚出去
Get out.

46
00:04:21,156 --> 00:04:23,676
先生 你是埃塞克斯号上唯一的幸存者
You are the last survivor or the Essex, Sir.

47
00:04:23,876 --> 00:04:25,976
如果你不说出来 谁还能讲出事实
If you won't talk, who will?

48
00:04:26,076 --> 00:04:30,136
你没听见我的话吗 出去
You do not hear me, leave now.

49
00:04:34,816 --> 00:04:37,096
你不能走 拜托 就一会儿  他没心情谈
- You mustn't go, please, just take a minute... - He's in no mind to talk, and

50
00:04:37,206 --> 00:04:39,566
我不是大老远来就是为了被羞辱和浪费时间
I haven't come all this way to be humiliated and waste my time.

51
00:04:39,616 --> 00:04:41,386
拜托了 梅尔维尔 先生
Please, Mr. Melville,

52
00:04:42,026 --> 00:04:47,996
他从来不跟别人谈论埃塞克斯号 包括我 从不
he won't talk about the Essex to me, to anyone... never has... never.

53
00:04:48,396 --> 00:04:50,966
我一点都不了解他
I don't know anything about him.

54
00:04:51,166 --> 00:04:58,386
他的精神在受折磨 需要救赎
His soul is... in torment, and in need of confession.

55
00:04:59,426 --> 00:05:02,716
拜托了 请让我和他谈 拜托了
Please, just let me talk to him... please.

56
00:05:08,586 --> 00:05:10,306
亲爱的
Love,

57
00:05:13,656 --> 00:05:17,486
我觉得和这个年轻人谈会对你有好处
I believe it would do you good to talk to the man.

58
00:05:18,276 --> 00:05:19,406
不
No!

59
00:05:22,956 --> 00:05:25,006
你听着
You listen well!

60
00:05:25,506 --> 00:05:29,186
你酗酒要死的时候谁撑着这个家了
Who holds this place together while you drink yourself to death?

61
00:05:29,746 --> 00:05:33,196
你必须和这个年轻人谈
You WILL talk with this man, as much as is necessary...

62
00:05:33,506 --> 00:05:35,436
才能保住你的钱
to keep the money.

63
00:05:36,496 --> 00:05:39,606
你知道我们的处境 汤姆
You know our circumstances, Tom.

64
00:05:50,466 --> 00:05:53,386
我只说必要的
Only as much as is necessary.

65
00:05:57,736 --> 00:06:00,056
我去拿威士忌
I'll get whiskey.

66
00:06:04,756 --> 00:06:09,836
我忘了在信里提到我曾经是一名捕鲸手
I neglected to mention it in my letter, but I was a whaler once.

67
00:06:11,046 --> 00:06:14,906
<i>有过一次出航 新手
<i>One trip. I mean... green hand.

68
00:06:14,976 --> 00:06:17,666
那么你应该都经历过了
So, you've seen it all.

69
00:06:19,196 --> 00:06:21,566
我妻子读过你的书
My wife read your books.

70
00:06:21,766 --> 00:06:26,096
她很喜欢 很高兴听到
- She enjoyed them. - Happy to hear it.

71
00:06:27,146 --> 00:06:30,536
销量很好 但我估计这个故事
They had good sales, but I think that THIS story

72
00:06:31,296 --> 00:06:34,876
甚至能超过我销量不错的第一部小说
could surpass even the success of my first novel... which did quite well.

73
00:06:35,076 --> 00:06:38,816
又一个你的航海轶事
Another of your seafaring yarns.

74
00:06:42,006 --> 00:06:44,876
你听说过霍索恩吗 梅尔维尔先生
Have you read Hawthorne, Mr. Melville?

75
00:06:45,046 --> 00:06:50,026
当下有一名作家 一个大作家
Now, there's a writer, a great writer.

76
00:06:50,186 --> 00:06:51,686
他是的
He is.

77
00:06:54,056 --> 00:06:57,266
但他不在这儿 因为我自己的原因
But he is not here, and I am...

78
00:06:57,466 --> 00:07:00,096
我在这儿
for my own particular reasons.

79
00:07:08,736 --> 00:07:12,876
我会告诉你埃塞克斯号 我相信你会失望的
I'll tell you of the Essex, I believe you will be disappointed,

80
00:07:13,076 --> 00:07:15,876
但我说的每个字都是真实的
but every word I say will be true.

81
00:07:17,366 --> 00:07:21,546
埃塞克斯号的故事就是两个男人的故事
The story of the Essex is the story of two men...

82
00:07:23,056 --> 00:07:24,956
乔治·波拉德船长
Captain George Pollard,

83
00:07:25,616 --> 00:07:29,626
和他大副 欧文·查斯
and his first mate, Owen Chase.

84
00:07:29,826 --> 00:07:33,086
欧文 你不能迟到
Owen, you don't want to be late.

85
00:07:33,286 --> 00:07:38,406
我会到那儿的 再说了 不能让我们的女儿睡在破陋的房子里对吧
I'll be there, besides, can't have our daughter sleeping under a leaky roof, can we?

86
00:07:38,606 --> 00:07:40,706
你为什么那么肯定是女儿
What makes you so sure it's a girl?

87
00:07:40,906 --> 00:07:45,926
肯定是的 她会提醒我你这么固执为什么我还是爱你
Well, it has to be, so she can remind me why I have to love you, and you being stubborn.

88
00:07:46,126 --> 00:07:48,826
如果是女儿她会更像你而不是我
If it's to to be a daughter she'll be a version of you, not me.

89
00:07:48,976 --> 00:07:51,456
金发而且一心想征服世界
Blond locks and determined to conquer the world.

90
00:07:52,346 --> 00:07:55,156
我想过了今天你会用那件外套换一套制服
I suppose after today you'll be tradin' in that tunic for a uniform.

91
00:07:55,276 --> 00:08:00,616
没错 终于能离开这破地方去赚个区艾瑟 船长该住的房子了
That's right, finally out of this patch of dirt for a captain's house in Quaise.

92
00:08:00,806 --> 00:08:03,786
我不想住在周边都是古板的邻居的房子里
I don't need one of those houses in town with stuffy neighbors.

93
00:08:03,986 --> 00:08:05,926
这里有足够供我们一家三口居住的地方
There's plenty room here for the three of us.

94
00:08:06,026 --> 00:08:10,846
有时候你的温情真让人受不了
Ya know, sometimes your kind heart and good nature is just unbearable.

95
00:08:12,516 --> 00:08:14,346
去做你的船长吧
Go get your captaincy.

96
00:08:58,026 --> 00:08:59,636
<i>- 你下注 1美元9分
<i>- What's your bid? - One ninety.

97
00:09:00,306 --> 00:09:02,396
<i>我用2美元买到了一千加仑
<i>I've got a thousand gallons at two dollars!

98
00:09:02,486 --> 00:09:03,876
<i>我占40份
<i>I'll take 40 shares.

99
00:09:05,216 --> 00:09:08,136
<i>卖家 卖家 在这
<i>Seller, seller, over here!

100
00:09:12,396 --> 00:09:16,016
<i>克雷斯拉回来了1600桶
<i>Criterion's back with a fine haul, 1600 barrels.

101
00:09:16,246 --> 00:09:21,166
伦敦市场新纪录 50磅银器换灯芯
A new record, 50 pounds Sterling for headmatter on the London market.

102
00:09:32,816 --> 00:09:33,796
早上好 查斯先生
Good morning Mr. Chase.

103
00:09:33,896 --> 00:09:35,816
马森先生 请进
- Mr. Mason. - Come in, please.

104
00:09:38,326 --> 00:09:40,226
我的合伙人 本杰明·福勒
My partner, Benjamin Fuller.

105
00:09:40,426 --> 00:09:42,816
早上好 先生 请坐
- Good morning, Sir. - Do sit down.

106
00:09:47,566 --> 00:09:51,336
查斯先生 我们希望你知道我们对你
Mr. Chase, I do hope you realize how satisfied we are

107
00:09:51,606 --> 00:09:53,986
为我们多年的工作有多么满意
with the work you've done for us over the years.

108
00:09:54,036 --> 00:09:55,106
谢谢 先生
Oh, thank you, Sir.

109
00:09:55,306 --> 00:09:57,936
我们其中一艘船 埃塞克斯号
And one of our ships, the Essex

110
00:09:58,136 --> 00:10:02,186
已经花大价钱修整好准备出海了
has just be refitted at great expense and is to go to sea.

111
00:10:02,836 --> 00:10:04,936
因为在她身上花了大价钱
Now, having made such an investment in her,

112
00:10:05,016 --> 00:10:08,416
我们希望确保她在最适合的人手里
we want to be sure she's in the best possible hands.

113
00:10:08,666 --> 00:10:10,466
所以
So...

114
00:10:10,576 --> 00:10:14,196
我们很高兴邀请你成为这艘船的
it gives us great pleasure to offer you a position aboard her...

115
00:10:15,036 --> 00:10:16,636
大副
as first mate.

116
00:10:19,876 --> 00:10:21,786
大副 是的
- As first mate? - Uh-hum.

117
00:10:22,296 --> 00:10:26,096
马森先生 你许诺过我上次出航带回来1500桶的话
Mr. Mason, you... you promised me command of a ship after my last voyage when

118
00:10:26,196 --> 00:10:30,886
会让我当一艘船的船长 你保证过的
I brought you back 1500 barrels, do you remember? You gave me your word.

119
00:10:31,086 --> 00:10:33,666
那个承诺要推迟了
That promise must now be deferred.

120
00:10:33,866 --> 00:10:37,136
像别人一样我们最近行情不好
Like everyone else we've had a mean time recently.

121
00:10:37,216 --> 00:10:38,656
我看不是
Well, never on my watch.

122
00:10:38,756 --> 00:10:43,596
楠塔基特主宰了全球市场 这点不能变
Nantucket now dominates the world market, that must not change.

123
00:10:43,796 --> 00:10:46,746
没有时间来试验
This is no time for experimentation.

124
00:10:46,946 --> 00:10:50,396
埃塞克斯号必须由乔治·波拉德指挥
The Essex will be captained by George Pollard,

125
00:10:50,406 --> 00:10:53,486
伟大的捕鲸家族的后裔
scion of a great whaling family.

126
00:10:53,966 --> 00:10:57,326
<i>他的父亲也是我们的老主顾
<i>His father also happens to be our patron.

127
00:10:57,526 --> 00:11:01,716
<i>血统 查斯先生 你可以有出色的航海技能
<i>Blood, Mr. Chase, you can have all the voyages under your belt you want

128
00:11:01,916 --> 00:11:03,766
<i>但血统还是更重要
<i>but blood will always win out.

129
00:11:03,866 --> 00:11:06,726
但是血统不会帮你的船装满油回来 马森先生
Yes, well, blood's not gonna fill the ship with oil, Mr. Mason.

130
00:11:06,836 --> 00:11:10,626
<i>要成功指挥船 船长需要被人尊重 如果别人不尊重他怎么办
<i>To successfully command, a captain needs respect, now, what if the men don't respect him?

131
00:11:11,126 --> 00:11:13,276
你就要确保别人尊重他
You will make sure that they do.

132
00:11:13,476 --> 00:11:15,246
再见 先生们
Good day, Gentlemen.

133
00:11:15,346 --> 00:11:17,896
我理解你的失落
I understand your disappointment.

134
00:11:17,946 --> 00:11:18,946
所以
So...

135
00:11:19,636 --> 00:11:22,086
115金币
A one-fifteenth lay.

136
00:11:23,986 --> 00:11:26,926
我从来没有给新长官支付过这么多
And that's more than I've ever paid any first officer.

137
00:11:27,026 --> 00:11:31,666
如果你带回来2000桶油 我向你保证
And if you bring back 2000 barrels of oil, I'll give you my word,

138
00:11:32,966 --> 00:11:35,386
<i>下次你就会是船长
<i>next time you WILL have your captaincy.

139
00:11:35,586 --> 00:11:38,446
你之前给过我保证来 马森先生
You've given me your word before, Mr. Mason.

140
00:11:40,476 --> 00:11:43,036
这次我需要书面保证
So, this time I'll take it in writing.

141
00:11:56,006 --> 00:12:01,516
波拉德船长 我们和查斯先生达成了协议
Captain Pollard, we've just had a most agreeable conversation with Mr. Chase,

142
00:12:01,716 --> 00:12:03,746
他会很荣幸服务于您
who'd be honored to serve under you.

143
00:12:05,306 --> 00:12:07,346
我很高兴听到
I'm glad to hear it.

144
00:12:07,546 --> 00:12:09,876
现在我得照顾个没经验的
Now I'm to babysit a greenhorn.

145
00:12:10,076 --> 00:12:14,226
一个含着他妈的金勺长大的船长了
Some cheerless Nantucket born with a damned silver spoon in his mouth.

146
00:12:14,426 --> 00:12:16,076
我真应该当面拒绝
I should have thrown their offer back in their faces.

147
00:12:16,146 --> 00:12:20,046
为什么 你已经拿到书面承诺了
Why? You now have the offer of command in writing.

148
00:12:20,146 --> 00:12:23,606
骗子的世界什么都是假的 即使是书面承诺
Yes, well, a liar's word is worthless, even ON paper.

149
00:12:33,486 --> 00:12:36,826
你知道即使你是商人我还是会爱上你的
You know I'd love you just as much if you were a merchant captain?

150
00:12:37,026 --> 00:12:38,856
<i>你不能离开两年之久
<i>And you wouldn't be gone for two years.

151
00:12:39,056 --> 00:12:40,436
我不会离开两年之久的
I won't be gone two years.

152
00:12:40,486 --> 00:12:43,516
贝德福德家的捕鲸人上周回来了 离开了有三年
A Bedford whaler came back last week was gone three.

153
00:12:44,176 --> 00:12:46,756
她失去了两个男人 而且惊魂落魄
She lost two men and still with her hull half empty.

154
00:12:46,846 --> 00:12:49,636
他们是贝德福德家 没有我在
Well, they were from Bedford and they didn't have me aboard.

155
00:12:54,286 --> 00:12:56,326
婊子养的
Son of a bitch!

156
00:12:58,726 --> 00:13:01,276
我要指挥我自己的船
I will captain my own ship...

157
00:13:02,356 --> 00:13:03,896
一艘捕鲸船
a whaling ship.

158
00:13:04,806 --> 00:13:07,126
靠他们我们只能永远在这个鬼地方
Up to them all we'd ever have is a patch of dirt

159
00:13:07,196 --> 00:13:08,546
我不会让这发生的 佩吉
and that's not going to happen, Peggy.

160
00:13:08,676 --> 00:13:10,996
你父亲也是这么说的 你不能这么说
Those'd be your father's words, not yours.

161
00:13:11,086 --> 00:13:12,636
他的话怎么了
What's wrong with his words?

162
00:13:13,476 --> 00:13:16,336
他想要为家人为自己争取
He wanted things for his family, for himself.

163
00:13:17,026 --> 00:13:19,766
他是个梦想家 欧文 是的 他是
- He was a dreamer, Owen - Yes, he was.

164
00:13:20,136 --> 00:13:23,686
梦想大海 不带那些废物们出海
Dreamed of the sea and never got to sea with men like them.

165
00:13:23,726 --> 00:13:25,936
至少他看到了他的孩子出生
At least he got to see his children born.

166
00:13:34,296 --> 00:13:36,616
我只能干这些
It's all I know.

167
00:13:40,046 --> 00:13:42,056
对不起
I'm sorry.

168
00:13:44,166 --> 00:13:45,966
我嫁给了一个捕鲸人
I married a whaleman.

169
00:13:55,476 --> 00:13:59,336
我会尽快回来 我发誓
I'll come back as quick as the sun is night, I swear.

170
00:14:09,376 --> 00:14:13,726
一定要回来 向我保证
Please come back... promise me.

171
00:14:15,956 --> 00:14:18,846
我已经向你发誓了 你还要我保证
I already swore to you, now you want me to promise, too.

172
00:14:23,186 --> 00:14:25,116
我保证
I promise.

173
00:14:39,366 --> 00:14:41,266
孩子 跟你说句话
Son, a word with you.

174
00:14:43,576 --> 00:14:47,896
当船长 你不能当他们的朋友 你是他们的长官
To be a captain, you cannot be a friend, you are their superior.

175
00:14:48,316 --> 00:14:51,106
别忘了这点 让别人记住这点
Never forget that, never let THEM forget that.

176
00:14:52,046 --> 00:14:53,346
谢谢
Thank you, son.

177
00:14:53,546 --> 00:14:57,446
你的曾祖父和其他人创立了这个行业
Your great-grandfather and a few others created this industry.

178
00:14:57,646 --> 00:15:02,016
没有我们 没有你们 世界将会陷入黑暗
Without us, without you, the world plunges into darkness.

179
00:15:02,216 --> 00:15:05,226
我希望能让家族名誉生辉 先生
I hope to bring honor to the Pollard family name, Sir.

180
00:15:11,656 --> 00:15:18,136
<i>啊 上帝创造了巨大的鲸 体长无比的神奇怪物
<i>Thou didst, O Lord, create the mighty whale, That wondrous monster of a mighty length;

181
00:15:18,716 --> 00:15:22,366
<i>头硕身庞尾又阔 无边雄力人难度
<i>Beyond conception his unmeasured strength.

182
00:15:22,566 --> 00:15:28,386
<i>恒古上帝宥永生 吾侪荏弱落凡尘
<i>But, everlasting God, thou dost ordain that we, poor feeble mortals

183
00:15:28,446 --> 00:15:33,496
<i>妻儿一家须偷生
<i>should engage ourselves, our wives and children to maintain,

184
00:15:33,546 --> 00:15:38,126
<i>赖此巨物维生存
<i>This dreadful monster with a martial rage.

185
00:15:40,706 --> 00:15:46,356
<i>啊 上帝 用您的荣耀之光照亮这些男人
<i>O Father, grant that your glorious light shine on these men,

186
00:15:46,406 --> 00:15:49,226
<i>保佑他们丰收的航程
<i>and assure them a prosperous voyage,

187
00:15:49,276 --> 00:15:53,106
<i>保佑他们安全归来
<i>that they may return SAFELY unto the womb ship.

188
00:15:53,486 --> 00:15:57,026
<i>楠塔基特的白鲸油
<i>So that the white whales of Nantucket whale oil

189
00:15:57,226 --> 00:16:00,486
<i>可以继续照亮我们的房屋
<i>may continue to keep light in our homes,

190
00:16:00,686 --> 00:16:07,146
<i>照亮我们的街道 为工业机器提供燃料
<i>city streets safe from sin in the night, fuel the machines of industry,

191
00:16:07,346 --> 00:16:09,836
<i>推动我们伟大的国家前进
<i>drive our great nation forward,

192
00:16:10,036 --> 00:16:16,436
<i>我们文明种族进步 我们祈祷
<i>as our noble species evolves. In Your name, we pray.

193
00:16:25,206 --> 00:16:28,246
现在是几月
So, what month is this?

194
00:16:28,446 --> 00:16:32,006
年末了 我们是最后一批出海的船只了
Oh, late in the year, we were one of the last ships to go out.

195
00:16:32,376 --> 00:16:35,506
也是为什么我和我朋友巴尔齐莱有卧铺
Which is why my friend Barzillai and I got a berth.

196
00:16:35,706 --> 00:16:40,646
听着 我当时14岁
Look, I was fourteen... fourteen.

197
00:16:41,656 --> 00:16:44,416
<i>尼克森 别站着 干活
<i>Nickerson, you're standin' around, boy! Move!

198
00:16:44,516 --> 00:16:48,066
<i>第一次出海 很害怕 更害怕显露出来
<i>First time at sea, scared, more scared to show it.

199
00:16:48,166 --> 00:16:50,106
<i>巴尔齐莱当时17岁
<i>Barzillai was seventeen.

200
00:16:50,306 --> 00:16:54,856
<i>在码头长大的孤儿</i>都等不及被别人视作大人
<i>Orphans, grew up on the wharf,</i> both in a hurry to be called men.

201
00:16:56,626 --> 00:17:00,866
<i>你们慢腾腾干嘛 装船 快 快
<i>What are you all guys waiting for? Get it aboard! C'mon! Haul away...!

202
00:17:00,966 --> 00:17:03,026
他们戴的是饰针是什么
What are those pins they're wearing?

203
00:17:03,076 --> 00:17:04,386
那些是白鲸徽章 汤姆斯
Those are whale pins, Thomas.

204
00:17:04,716 --> 00:17:06,266
我怎么才能得到一个
How do I get one of them?

205
00:17:06,316 --> 00:17:09,046
你得用长矛刺杀一头白鲸
Well, you've gotta thrust a killing lance.

206
00:17:09,246 --> 00:17:11,746
那是世界上最大的怪物
The largest beast ever to breathe on the earth.

207
00:17:12,546 --> 00:17:15,566
<i>尼克森 把那绿色的东西给邦德先生
<i>Nickerson, get the green stuff to Mr. Bond.

208
00:17:16,436 --> 00:17:18,176
<i>快点 妈的
<i>Make it quick, damn it.

209
00:17:19,276 --> 00:17:21,696
我总有一天会有一堆那东西
I shall have twelve of those one day.

210
00:17:26,606 --> 00:17:27,716
把它们放到匣子里
Put 'em on the Grandira casket.

211
00:17:27,856 --> 00:17:30,516
你也上船就说明一件事
Well, well, you being on board means only one thing.

212
00:17:30,566 --> 00:17:34,496
是啊 这船上至少有一人明白欧文·查斯是谁
Yep! At least there's one person on this ship who knows the truth about Owen Chase.

213
00:17:34,856 --> 00:17:37,366
不 可惜其他的船都已经满员了
No, but all the other ships have already crewed up.

214
00:17:37,466 --> 00:17:42,166
不不 我洗心革面了 欧文 问题是你呢
No, no, I'm a reformed man, Owen, the question is are YOU?

215
00:17:42,266 --> 00:17:44,586
别告诉我花花公子马修戒酒了
Don't tell me Matthew Joy has put down the bottle.

216
00:17:44,706 --> 00:17:48,196
我有罪 欧文·查斯能消消他的坏脾气了吗
I have sinned. Has Owen Chase put down his temper?

217
00:17:48,396 --> 00:17:50,086
平静的像教堂
Serene as the Church.

218
00:17:50,286 --> 00:17:52,326
照我看来
I'll believe THAT when I see it.

219
00:17:52,526 --> 00:17:58,566
考虑到我们的船长 我觉得你只能平静一小会儿
Given our captain I'll give your serenity about 48 hours.

220
00:17:59,476 --> 00:18:00,806
祝你好运
Good luck.

221
00:18:06,656 --> 00:18:10,386
波拉德 乔治·波拉德 欧文·查斯
- Pollard, George Pollard. - Owen Chase.

222
00:18:10,586 --> 00:18:15,146
查斯 你父亲的名字对吗 对 是的
- Chase, your father's name, isn't it? - Yes, it is.

223
00:18:15,346 --> 00:18:19,966
马上他要离开岛一段时间而我舒适得待在家
Very shortly he will be off island for some time and I'll be very much at home.

224
00:18:20,776 --> 00:18:26,356
我要说 我有点意外 通常船长可以选择自己的大副
I say, I was surprised, normally a captain gets to choose his first mate.

225
00:18:26,556 --> 00:18:28,776
如果是有经验的船长的话 是的
An experienced captain, yes.

226
00:18:28,976 --> 00:18:30,866
当人 你可以理解老头的意思
Of course, you can understand from the owners' point of view,

227
00:18:30,976 --> 00:18:33,416
他们想让自己的财产在适合的人手里
they wanted to put their investments in the hands of men.

228
00:18:34,126 --> 00:18:34,916
确实
Indeed.

229
00:18:35,016 --> 00:18:37,956
他们也许想要多些保障
They probably wanted a little extra reassurance, that's all.

230
00:18:38,156 --> 00:18:41,046
看着点我 如果我做错什么了告诉我
Well, DO keep an eye on me, let me know if I'm doing anything wrong.

231
00:18:41,186 --> 00:18:43,376
我不会迟疑的 船长
I'd have it not other way, Captain.

232
00:18:55,586 --> 00:18:56,356
起锚
Shore up the anchor.

233
00:18:56,396 --> 00:18:58,596
起风了 顶部横杆放下了吗 好
- Head's in the wind, is the top rail off? <i>- Aye.

234
00:18:58,716 --> 00:19:00,006
克拉德 掌舵 好
- Collard, Take the helm! - Aye!

235
00:19:00,126 --> 00:19:01,186
花花公子 扬帆
Mr. Joy, make sail.

236
00:19:01,286 --> 00:19:03,866
科尔 查普尔 守在起锚器旁
Mr. Cole, Mr. Chappel, stand by this anchor!

237
00:19:24,726 --> 00:19:26,826
查普尔 掌舵
Mr. Chappel, take the helm!

238
00:19:28,796 --> 00:19:32,016
为什么帆布还没有松开
Boyd! Why aren't those braces laid out?

239
00:19:46,506 --> 00:19:48,256
打开帆 妈的
Set the sail, god damn it!

240
00:19:55,306 --> 00:19:57,056
跑开
Heading to scram.

241
00:19:57,156 --> 00:20:00,126
船长 注意头上 后面 船长
- Captain! Heads up! - Behind you head, Captain!

242
00:20:03,056 --> 00:20:06,446
怎么了 谢泼德 帆布缠住了 长官
- What happened, Mr. Sheppard? - The jalousie felled the sheet, Sir.

243
00:20:08,326 --> 00:20:11,356
帆布缠住了 查斯 他办不到
- The jalousie's jammed! - Chase, she still won't clear!

244
00:20:22,056 --> 00:20:23,856
<i>当心
<i>Watch your step!

245
00:20:24,056 --> 00:20:26,166
帆布 欧文
It's the jalousie, Owen!

246
00:20:37,506 --> 00:20:38,946
走开
Stand clear!

247
00:21:06,016 --> 00:21:08,216
<i>干的漂亮 查斯
<i>Nice piece of work, Mr. Chase!

248
00:21:20,606 --> 00:21:22,566
如果两周内能到佛得角
If we make Cape Verdes in the next 2 weeks we'll

249
00:21:22,616 --> 00:21:25,926
我们有很大几率能按时到太平洋
have a decent chance of reaching the Pacific on schedule.

250
00:21:28,476 --> 00:21:30,436
玉米棒 查斯
Corn, Mr. Chase?

251
00:21:30,586 --> 00:21:33,736
不需要 谢谢 从来不喜欢
No, thank you, Sir, never did have much of a taste for it.

252
00:21:34,636 --> 00:21:36,016
太怪了
That's odd.

253
00:21:36,516 --> 00:21:40,526
你爸在科德角是种玉米的吧 是的
- So, your father grew corn on Cape Cod. - That's right, he did.

254
00:21:40,726 --> 00:21:43,916
你也猜到了 我那时天天吃这个吃腻了
As you can imagine, I suddenly grew tired of eating it every day.

255
00:21:46,306 --> 00:21:52,136
种玉米 秋葵 大豆 然后他进了监狱
Corn, okra, beans, I believe? Before he went to jail.

256
00:21:54,656 --> 00:21:57,366
花花公子 听起来熟悉吗
Are you familiar with this story, Mr. Joy?

257
00:21:59,106 --> 00:22:04,596
你知道查斯是因为他的父亲进监狱才变成孤儿的吗
Were you aware that Mr. Chase was effectively orphaned due to his father's incarceration?

258
00:22:04,746 --> 00:22:08,136
我们都有不同的经历
Well, we all have our paths to sea.

259
00:22:08,626 --> 00:22:11,726
所以还是不要问太多问题为好
That's a motive to not ask too many questions.

260
00:22:13,116 --> 00:22:15,636
一定不容易吧
Can't have been easy though, yet...

261
00:22:16,346 --> 00:22:20,066
楠塔基特最伟大的航海家族收留你
You had Nantucket's great seafaring family to adopt you.

262
00:22:20,266 --> 00:22:23,806
很久没有楠塔基特人称呼我陆人
This is far from the first time I've been called a landsman...

263
00:22:23,906 --> 00:22:29,976
或者提醒我不是他们一家人了
or off-islander by some Nantucket reminding me how I am NOT part of their family.

264
00:22:30,696 --> 00:22:35,556
请允许我 船长 我要去分配捕鲸船和值班了
Now, if the captain will excuse me, there are whale boats and watches to assign.

265
00:22:41,986 --> 00:22:45,246
不 船长 滴酒不沾
- No, Sir, not for me. - Not a drop?

266
00:22:45,346 --> 00:22:51,006
不 船长 就像我说的 有时候少问问题更好
No, Sir, like I said, sometimes the fewer questions one asks, the better.

267
00:23:10,456 --> 00:23:12,286
花花公子 这有个漂亮姑娘
That's a gorgeous girl, Mr. Joy.

268
00:23:12,336 --> 00:23:16,156
远东的鲸骨上刻的
Region of move me that, carved from a Far East whalebone.

269
00:23:16,356 --> 00:23:18,516
不许碰
No touching!

270
00:23:18,716 --> 00:23:19,816
我一直以为你已经结婚了
I always thought you were married anyway.

271
00:23:19,926 --> 00:23:22,176
是的 但看她
I am, and there she is.

272
00:23:22,376 --> 00:23:25,086
这是她的鼻子
Well, that's her nose anyway.

273
00:23:25,966 --> 00:23:27,746
恭喜 女士们
Congratulations, ladies.

274
00:23:30,066 --> 00:23:32,696
今天启航干的不错
That was a fine job trimin' sails today.

275
00:23:32,896 --> 00:23:36,656
我从来没有过这么一群捕鲸人
A sorrier pack of deck-whalers I don't think I've ever seen.

276
00:23:38,146 --> 00:23:40,366
查普尔 长官
- Mr. Chappel. - Sir.

277
00:23:40,566 --> 00:23:42,156
船长鱼叉手
Captain's harpooner.

278
00:23:42,356 --> 00:23:45,746
劳伦斯 你做我的 遵命 长官
- Mr. Lawrence, you'll be mine. - Aye, Sir.

279
00:23:45,946 --> 00:23:50,606
彼得森 二副的鱼叉手
And Mr. Peterson, second mate's harpooner.

280
00:23:50,806 --> 00:23:51,506
遵命 长官
Aye, Sir.

281
00:23:51,606 --> 00:23:56,096
一船上六人 首要一点要警觉
There'll be six men to a boat, first rules in the row, six bells sharp.

282
00:23:56,196 --> 00:23:59,226
我们还没到哈利法克斯以东 长官
We're not even east of Halifax, Sir.

283
00:23:59,426 --> 00:24:03,336
你叫什么 克芬 亨利·克芬
- What's your name? - Coffin, Henry Coffin.

284
00:24:03,536 --> 00:24:05,606
<i>他是船长的表弟 长官
<i>He's the Captain's cousin, Sir.

285
00:24:06,926 --> 00:24:11,746
克芬先生 你觉得一头白鲸会知道自己在哈利法克斯以东吗
Well, well, Mr. Coffin, do you think a whale knows it's east of Halifax?

286
00:24:14,706 --> 00:24:18,486
我不知道你们原来是谁 或者怎么来的
I don't know who all of you are, or how you got here,

287
00:24:18,686 --> 00:24:21,666
你们中一些人可能甚至是重犯 在隐藏或者逃亡
Some of you probably have felonies, or are hidin' or on the run.

288
00:24:21,816 --> 00:24:26,806
没关系 我不关心 我对你们的要求只有一个
That's fine, I don't give a damn, but we interred you for just one thing...

289
00:24:27,016 --> 00:24:31,466
只有一个 就是鲸油
and one thing only, and that is whale oil.

290
00:24:31,666 --> 00:24:35,576
<i>我要装满2000桶油并尽快回家
<i>I intend to fill our 2000 barrels and be home as quickly as possible.

291
00:24:35,786 --> 00:24:39,376
即使天气好而且没有鲸出没 克芬先生
And even when the weather is fine and there ARE no whales, Mr. Coffin,

292
00:24:39,426 --> 00:24:44,086
<i>我们会放下船练习如何捕鲸
<i>we will lower the boats and practice all maneuvers</i> necessary in a capture of a whale.

293
00:24:44,186 --> 00:24:47,546
谁要是想偷懒就自己游回家 明白吗
And any man who is idle will find himself swimmin' to home. Is that understood?

294
00:24:47,726 --> 00:24:49,936
明白 长官
- Aye, sir. Aye, Sir. - Aye, Sir.

295
00:24:53,586 --> 00:24:57,156
小子 上甲板
Green horn, on deck!

296
00:25:00,006 --> 00:25:01,826
走
On ya go!

297
00:25:04,106 --> 00:25:06,476
遵命 遵命 陆人
Aye, aye, landsman.

298
00:25:06,576 --> 00:25:09,016
汤姆·尼克森 对吧 是的 长官
- Thomas Nickerson, right? - Aye, Sir.

299
00:25:09,216 --> 00:25:11,596
有些人一开始会觉得恶心
Ya know, some feel sick at first.

300
00:25:15,586 --> 00:25:18,936
拉我上去 这是最好的办法
- Pull me back up! - Best way to square up to King Neptune, Boy.

301
00:25:19,126 --> 00:25:20,616
求你了 拉我上去
Please, bring me up.

302
00:25:24,936 --> 00:25:26,896
好点了吗
Better now?

303
00:25:31,106 --> 00:25:33,486
长官 非常对不起
Sir, I am so sorry.

304
00:25:34,516 --> 00:25:37,796
你现在有故事写信回家告诉你母亲了
Well, now you got something to write home to your mother about.

305
00:25:42,326 --> 00:25:44,986
我母亲葬在史密斯山
My mother's buried up in Smith's Hill,

306
00:25:45,186 --> 00:25:47,566
我爸也是 他
and a stone for my father, too, he was...

307
00:25:47,666 --> 00:25:50,516
他在我出生前就葬身大海了
he was lost at sea before I was born.

308
00:25:51,396 --> 00:25:53,206
给我
Here, give me that.

309
00:25:55,666 --> 00:25:59,636
白鲸现在是你的家人了 是好是坏
The whale's is your family now, Boy, for better or for worse.

310
00:26:01,886 --> 00:26:03,626
坏处多是
For worse mostly.

311
00:26:06,136 --> 00:26:08,056
清理甲板 小子
Swab the deck, Kid!

312
00:26:24,626 --> 00:26:27,206
<i>你离学会捕鲸和航行还差远了
<i>You're a long way from base to be whaling and sailing.

313
00:26:27,256 --> 00:26:27,886
<i>是 长官
<i>Aye, aye, Captain.

314
00:26:28,986 --> 00:26:31,736
<i>你系错绳子了 是 长官
<i>- You got that line wrong, Nickerson. - Aye, Captain.

315
00:26:31,786 --> 00:26:34,146
<i>如果有必要我们会训练到日落
<i>We'll stay at this until sunlight if we have to.

316
00:26:34,346 --> 00:26:35,426
<i>是 长官
<i>Aye, Captain.

317
00:26:36,626 --> 00:26:37,946
鱼叉手准备乘船
Harpooners make ready to boat.

318
00:26:53,856 --> 00:26:55,826
雷 动作快点 我的错
- Need to move quicker, Mr. Ray! - My mistake.

319
00:26:55,966 --> 00:26:59,136
<i>没有女人玩了 查斯
<i>Ain't no more wee whores, Mr. Chase.

320
00:27:00,566 --> 00:27:01,966
<i>你现在是水手了 哈哈
<i>You're a sailor, now! Yeah!.

321
00:27:04,976 --> 00:27:07,226
干的不错 雷
Not bad, Mr. Ray, well done!

322
00:27:09,076 --> 00:27:11,346
<i>要习惯 伙计们 你们得像马一样工作
<i>Get used to it, mates, you gotta work like horses.

323
00:27:11,396 --> 00:27:13,896
查斯先生 长官
- Mr. Chase. - Sir.

324
00:27:14,846 --> 00:27:16,676
扬帆
Set stuns'ls.

325
00:27:17,276 --> 00:27:18,876
这样做好吗 长官 我们接近洋流
Is that wise, Sir, we're near the Gulf Stream.

326
00:27:19,186 --> 00:27:21,276
看这天气也还得缓慢前进
Best to be five knots fto even see the weather.

327
00:27:21,446 --> 00:27:23,366
我们落后两天行程了
We are two days behind.

328
00:27:23,566 --> 00:27:26,866
<i>你得在东风来临前弥补上时间
<i>You need to make up the time before we catch the east wind.

329
00:27:27,596 --> 00:27:29,326
扬帆
Set stuns'ls.

330
00:27:34,756 --> 00:27:36,236
扬帆
Set stuns'ls.

331
00:27:37,276 --> 00:27:39,146
拴绳 扬帆
Belay that, set stuns'ls.

332
00:27:40,016 --> 00:27:42,356
<i>克芬 松开帆 船长要提速
<i>Get her off, Mr. Coffin, the Captain wants speed!

333
00:27:42,406 --> 00:27:43,406
<i>遵命 长官
<i>Aye, Sir.

334
00:28:25,626 --> 00:28:28,656
<i>她老了 但是还能让我们爽 哈哈
<i>She might be old but she can still blow, boys!

335
00:28:38,066 --> 00:28:41,976
长官 右舷方向有一飓风团 我们需要马上降帆
Sir, a squall on the starboard route, we need to shorten the sail immediately.

336
00:28:42,176 --> 00:28:44,296
还不行 查斯
Not just yet, Mr. Chase.

337
00:28:44,436 --> 00:28:46,696
长官 我们以8里的速度驶向风暴
Sir, we are headed into a storm of more than 8 knots

338
00:28:46,796 --> 00:28:47,916
而且速度越来越快
and it's movin' faster than that.

339
00:28:48,356 --> 00:28:50,606
让它来吧 水手们在陆地上呆久变软弱了
Let it come, the men are soft from months on land, they

340
00:28:50,656 --> 00:28:54,156
他们需要一次洗礼 告诉他们工作开始了
need a good baptism, let them know our work has begun.

341
00:28:56,666 --> 00:28:59,816
如果我们不降帆并驶离 风暴一定会追上我们的
If we don't shorten sail and bear off it'll catch us on the beam.

342
00:28:59,996 --> 00:29:02,986
查斯 我们继续向前航行
Chase, we will stand on.

343
00:29:03,086 --> 00:29:07,336
劳伦斯 继续向前 继续向前 长官
- Mr. Lawrence, hold our course. - Holding course, Sir.

344
00:29:07,496 --> 00:29:09,336
我们这样前行会追到只差半天的航程
We'll lose half a day running like that.

345
00:29:09,476 --> 00:29:11,506
我们最后能赶上 如果我们的人
We'll scut the end of it, if the men can't

346
00:29:11,556 --> 00:29:14,406
不能应付这样的狂风 上帝也帮不了我们
handle a gust like this, then God help us all.

347
00:29:24,626 --> 00:29:27,136
<I>固定好一切应付糟糕的天气
<I>Best secure for heavy weather.

348
00:29:45,396 --> 00:29:49,106
准备好应付天气 邦德 我们要驶向风暴了
Best prepare for weather, Mr. Bond, we're headed into a squall.

349
00:30:07,816 --> 00:30:12,316
我们必须降帆离开这里 退下 查斯先生
- We must fall off and run with it. - Stand down, Mr. Chase.

350
00:30:12,416 --> 00:30:16,766
劳伦斯 航向不变 航向不变 长官
- Mr. Lawrence, hold your course. - Holding course, Sir.

351
00:30:32,336 --> 00:30:34,466
降帆 查斯
Shorten the sails, Mr. Chase.

352
00:30:39,976 --> 00:30:42,036
<i>我们要砍下那些帆
<i>We need to cut those sails down!

353
00:31:00,066 --> 00:31:02,776
船掉头 向陆地开
Turn the ship, head for land!

354
00:31:02,826 --> 00:31:05,966
不 损坏已经造成了
No, the damage is done!

355
00:31:09,826 --> 00:31:11,856
太晚了 太他妈晚了
It's too late, it's too god damned late!

356
00:31:12,056 --> 00:31:14,086
我们会撞上的
We'll be broadsided!

357
00:31:33,216 --> 00:31:34,756
抓牢
Hold on!

358
00:32:03,616 --> 00:32:05,346
<i>小心
<i>Look out!

359
00:32:26,606 --> 00:32:28,226
花花公子
Mr. Joy!

360
00:32:28,426 --> 00:32:31,486
<i>我们要割断 我知道了 欧文
<i>- We have to cut away the... - I've got it, Owen!

361
00:32:31,536 --> 00:32:33,406
<i>我们要让船摆正
<i>We have to set her up right!

362
00:33:26,976 --> 00:33:28,896
你说要见我 长官
You wish to see me, Sir.

363
00:33:30,476 --> 00:33:34,616
明天六时 你召集船员
At six bells tomorrow, you will assemble the crew,

364
00:33:35,126 --> 00:33:38,916
告知他们我们将返回楠塔基特维修
inform them that we will be returning to Nantucket for repairs.

365
00:33:39,116 --> 00:33:42,226
然后你向他们道歉你干涉了船长的命令
You will then apologize to them for interfering with a captain's order

366
00:33:42,396 --> 00:33:45,936
今天差点让船上的每个人都为此丧命
which nearly cost the lives of every man on this ship today.

367
00:33:46,136 --> 00:33:46,686
什么
What?

368
00:33:46,736 --> 00:33:49,546
返回到港口我会接受你的辞呈
I'll accept your resignation upon our return to port.

369
00:33:49,746 --> 00:33:51,146
就这些
That will be all.

370
00:33:51,346 --> 00:33:52,996
是你下命令杨帆的 长官
It was your order to set stuns'ls, Sir.

371
00:33:53,096 --> 00:33:55,916
命令没问题 这些人需要锻炼
That decision was sound, the men needed testing.

372
00:33:55,986 --> 00:33:58,046
你送他们进风暴
- You sent 'em into a storm? - That...

373
00:33:58,246 --> 00:33:59,766
那是幸运不好
was unlucky.

374
00:33:59,876 --> 00:34:03,906
不 这是缺乏航海经验 责怪运气只会显得软弱
No, it was bad seamanship, and blaming misfortune is just plain weakness.

375
00:34:04,006 --> 00:34:08,006
你他妈的无礼 你知道你在和谁说话吗
Damn your impertinence! Do you know who you're speaking to?

376
00:34:08,206 --> 00:34:12,346
我是船长乔治·波拉德 波拉德
My name is CAPTAIN George Pollard. POLLARD!

377
00:34:15,366 --> 00:34:19,536
而你查斯先生 无论你衣袖上钉多少白鲸徽章
And you Mr. Chase, no matter how many whale pins you may have on your lapel,

378
00:34:19,636 --> 00:34:21,866
你不过是个农民的儿子
are nothing more than the son of a farmer,

379
00:34:21,996 --> 00:34:25,176
仗势欺人才当上的长官
who's managed to bullying his way into an officer's tunic.

380
00:34:26,486 --> 00:34:28,376
滚出去
Now, get out!

381
00:34:31,126 --> 00:34:35,536
不带一桶油回港口是个错误 长官
To return to port without a single barrel of oil would be a mistake, Sir.

382
00:34:36,156 --> 00:34:41,156
<i>和名字是波拉德或者查斯没什么关系
<i>And not behoove a man whose name is Pollard... or Chase, for that matter.

383
00:34:41,356 --> 00:34:45,626
对我们来说最好是抓紧时间工作
And the best thing for both of us would be t'work all hours God sends us.

384
00:34:45,826 --> 00:34:48,826
把船装满油一年之内回到家
Fill this ship with oil, and be home inside a year

385
00:34:48,836 --> 00:34:51,566
然后各自分道扬镳
and rid of one another as quickly as possible.

386
00:34:54,366 --> 00:34:57,636
相信我 我也迫不及待这样做
Trust me, I have never been as desirous of that as you.

387
00:35:00,796 --> 00:35:03,586
当然 这由船长来做决定
Of course, that is the Captain's decision.

388
00:35:14,346 --> 00:35:16,936
<i>他们像一对新婚夫妇
<i>They were like a new married couple.

389
00:35:18,756 --> 00:35:21,586
新婚夫妇能容忍对方 梅尔维尔先生
A new married couple tolerate each other, Mr. Melville,

390
00:35:21,776 --> 00:35:24,506
<i>但新婚夫妇也能两败俱伤
<i>but a new married couple can also bring down a ship.

391
00:35:24,616 --> 00:35:28,116
你结婚了吗 梅尔维尔先生 是的
- You married, Mr. Melville? - I am.

392
00:35:28,366 --> 00:35:30,336
上帝仁慈
The Lord have mercy on ya.

393
00:35:31,226 --> 00:35:32,576
第一个孩子也快生了
First child on the way, too.

394
00:35:32,706 --> 00:35:36,726
那你的妻子知道你把所有的积蓄都带来了
So, does your good wife know that you brought all you have in the world here tonight,

395
00:35:36,826 --> 00:35:38,896
并且给了一个陌生人吗
and givin' it to a stranger?

396
00:35:39,706 --> 00:35:42,766
不知道 先生 你总让人吃惊
- No, Sir. - You're full of surprises, aren't you?

397
00:35:43,976 --> 00:35:49,706
那么 埃塞克斯号没有回港口
So... the Essex did not return to port.

398
00:35:49,906 --> 00:35:52,866
没有 她继续驶向大海
- She did not. - She continued out to sea.

399
00:35:52,926 --> 00:36:00,296
是的 但不久 我们都听到这个捕鲸人都盼望听到的吼声
Yes, she did, but before long, we heard the call this all whale men pray for...

400
00:36:00,926 --> 00:36:02,666
Ho!

401
00:36:03,756 --> 00:36:05,596
喷水
Blows!

402
00:36:06,056 --> 00:36:09,126
<i>是大家伙 喷水了
<i>A big one! Thar she blows!

403
00:36:09,176 --> 00:36:14,146
公的母的 拉姆斯德尔先生  他们是公的
<i>- White or sperm, Mr. Ramsdell? - Sperm whales they are!

404
00:36:15,116 --> 00:36:18,376
查斯先生  升起船只
Mr. Chase, hoist and swing boat.

405
00:36:18,506 --> 00:36:22,776
都来甲板
- All Hands! All hands on deck! <i>- All hands on deck!

406
00:36:29,166 --> 00:36:31,056
<i>放船
<i>Lower away!

407
00:36:34,166 --> 00:36:40,056
出海三个月 南大西洋

408
00:37:14,696 --> 00:37:17,686
再加把劲儿
Come on, put your back into it.!

409
00:37:27,306 --> 00:37:29,236
幼年鲸
There's the calf.

410
00:37:32,316 --> 00:37:35,666
幼年鲸 母鲸
- That's the calf? - That's the cow!

411
00:37:46,146 --> 00:37:48,926
<i>乖乖 那是我们的钱
<i>That's our boy! That's the money!

412
00:37:49,126 --> 00:37:51,166
尼克森 使劲
Nickerson! Push!

413
00:37:51,566 --> 00:37:54,036
够四十桶油了吧 五十桶
- Forty barrels there? - Fifty!

414
00:37:55,306 --> 00:37:57,016
<i>天 他是个大家伙
<i>Boy, he's a buster!

415
00:37:57,306 --> 00:38:01,486
<i>使劲划 要不然他要逃了
<i>Take the oars, lads! Quick or he'll god damn run!

416
00:38:01,656 --> 00:38:05,476
划起来 机灵点 伙计们 机灵点
Pull those oars up! Smartly, lads, smartly!

417
00:38:06,026 --> 00:38:07,776
<i>小心桨端
<i>Mind your oars!

418
00:38:08,466 --> 00:38:11,626
<i>拉姆斯德尔 准备绳 是 长官
<i>- Mr. Ramsdell, prepare the line. - Aye, Sir.

419
00:38:15,266 --> 00:38:16,886
<i>第一头是我的
<i>The first one's mine.

420
00:38:18,486 --> 00:38:20,156
瞄准她的弱点
Aim her to the free spot!

421
00:38:21,106 --> 00:38:23,986
<i>拉 拉 跟着
<i>Pull! Pull! Stay on him.

422
00:38:42,326 --> 00:38:45,426
伙计们 你们坐上了楠塔基特号第一班雪橇
You're on your first Nantucket sleigh ride, Boys.

423
00:38:59,376 --> 00:39:02,496
地球上最可怕的生物
The most fearsome creature to ever live on this earth.

424
00:39:16,676 --> 00:39:18,246
我的手
My hand!

425
00:39:26,156 --> 00:39:28,266
<i>你得把绳弄湿 尼克森
<i>You need to wet the line, Nickerson.

426
00:39:40,846 --> 00:39:43,796
<i>只剩140英寻的绳子了 查斯先生
<i>A hundred forty fathoms' of line left, Mr. Chase.

427
00:39:52,366 --> 00:39:54,856
<i>只剩80英寻的绳子了 长官
<i>Eighty fathoms' of line left, Sir.

428
00:39:59,736 --> 00:40:01,826
<i>他会把我们拖到水里的
<i>He's gonna pull us under!

429
00:40:03,556 --> 00:40:06,186
马修 我要你的绳子 给我绳
- Matthew, I need your line! - Feed the line!

430
00:40:06,386 --> 00:40:08,676
<i>彼得森给我绳子 是的 长官
<i>- Peterson give me the line! - Aye, Sir.

431
00:40:09,436 --> 00:40:13,526
<i>把那绳给我 彼得森 我们只剩60英寻的绳子了 长官
<i>- Give me that line, Mr. Peterson. - We're down to 60 fathoms' of line left, Sir.

432
00:40:15,516 --> 00:40:18,206
<i>20英寻了 查斯先生 松开绳
<i>- Twenty fathoms, Mr. Chase! - Tie it off!

433
00:40:22,716 --> 00:40:24,206
快
Go!

434
00:40:37,006 --> 00:40:39,066
彼得森 你来 是 长官
- Peterson, lay on! - Aye, Sir.

435
00:40:39,866 --> 00:40:42,286
还剩多长的绳子
How many fathoms can he draw?

436
00:40:47,056 --> 00:40:48,766
不 不 等等
No, no, no, wait!

437
00:40:53,406 --> 00:40:55,406
欧文 不 不是现在
- Owen! - Oh, no, not yet!

438
00:40:55,506 --> 00:40:59,396
别碰那绳 只剩50英寻了 长官
- Don't touch that line. <i>- Down to 50 fathoms, Sir.

439
00:41:01,586 --> 00:41:04,516
欧文 他妈的 我说了不要动
- Owen! God damn it! - I said don't touch it!

440
00:41:04,566 --> 00:41:05,566
<i>剩30英寻了 花花公子
<i>Thirty fathoms left, Mr. Joy.

441
00:41:10,676 --> 00:41:12,746
<i>剩10英寻了 长官
<i>Ten fathoms left, Sir!

442
00:42:36,196 --> 00:42:38,386
真是漫长的过程
It's been a long drive.

443
00:42:55,986 --> 00:42:57,386
油中的脂肪
Blubber in the oil.

444
00:42:58,866 --> 00:43:00,196
<i>它们要吃掉你的钱了
<i>They're gonna eat your money.

445
00:43:00,296 --> 00:43:02,666
<i>滚开 混账畜生
<i>Get out of there, you sons of bitches!

446
00:43:05,936 --> 00:43:08,486
<i>- 你拿到了吗 拿到了 查斯
<i>- You got it? - Got it, Chase.

447
00:43:12,086 --> 00:43:13,916
看起来怎么样 不怎么样
- How's it lookin'? - Not good.

448
00:43:16,376 --> 00:43:17,796
就这么多了
That's it.

449
00:43:21,456 --> 00:43:23,946
查斯先生 什么
- Mr. Chase, Sir? - Yep.

450
00:43:23,996 --> 00:43:26,376
长官 就这么多了 我们拿不到更多了
That's all of it, Sir, we can't get anymore out.

451
00:43:26,496 --> 00:43:29,186
那就是金矿 伙计们 继续挖
That's the gold in there, Boys, c'mon, keep diggin'.

452
00:43:29,376 --> 00:43:33,316
我块头太大下不去 得找个身材小的
- I'm too big to really go down there. - Then find someone who can.

453
00:43:38,636 --> 00:43:40,986
尼克森 过来小子
Nickerson, come here boy!

454
00:43:42,896 --> 00:43:45,226
<i>嘿 我喊你过来
<i>Hey! I said c'mere!

455
00:43:48,366 --> 00:43:50,096
爬进去
Climb on in with 'im.

456
00:43:50,986 --> 00:43:52,276
<i>来啊 汤姆斯
<i>Come on, Thomas.

457
00:43:52,776 --> 00:43:56,326
<i>这里面的东西可比它的肉值钱多了
<i>What's in there is worth a HELLEVA lot more than what they're boilin' down.

458
00:44:01,506 --> 00:44:06,226
长官 我不行 对不起 我做不了
Sir, I can't, I'm sorry. I can't.

459
00:44:06,306 --> 00:44:09,766
你自己进去或者我让你睡在里面
You get down there, or I'll have you sleep down there.

460
00:44:11,826 --> 00:44:14,516
你用牙齿把这东西咬住 小子
You best put that between your teeth, Boy.

461
00:44:14,676 --> 00:44:17,386
它里面臭得很
It tastes worse than the Devil's asshole down there.

462
00:44:21,006 --> 00:44:22,116
谢谢
Thank you.

463
00:44:27,496 --> 00:44:31,326
抱歉 尼克森 我的枕头送你
- Sorry. <i>- Here, Nickerson, take my pillow with ya!

464
00:44:33,866 --> 00:44:35,506
下去
Down ya go.

465
00:44:51,166 --> 00:44:54,146
一个人在里面能更了解自己
A man gets to know himself down there.

466
00:44:56,556 --> 00:45:01,286
他们有送你进一头鲸的头里面吗 没有 他们饶了我
- Did they ever send you into a whale's head? - No, I was spared.

467
00:45:01,856 --> 00:45:04,956
那里面才是宝藏所在
Well, that's where the treasure is.

468
00:45:06,706 --> 00:45:08,976
我永远都不会忘记那第一头
I'll never forget that first bull.

469
00:45:10,366 --> 00:45:15,266
47桶油 当然 幸福很短暂
Forty-seven barrels... of course, the happiness was short lived.

470
00:45:15,316 --> 00:45:17,756
那片水域没有鲸鱼可捕了
The waters had all been fished out?

471
00:45:17,906 --> 00:45:23,506
是的 所以我们向更远处前进
That they had. So, we headed further out.

472
00:45:27,186 --> 00:45:29,126
在那一个月之后
It was a month around the Horn.

473
00:45:31,086 --> 00:45:34,236
<i>离开了南大西洋
<i>Left the South Atlantic behind with a sliver of hope

474
00:45:34,286 --> 00:45:36,666
